        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer18678243" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16479086813600026411">This was a wonderful book. I am generally *not* a fan of short stories. I like stories that with lots of character development and there isn&apos;t time for that in short stories. Maybe this collection was improved by already &quot;knowing&quot; the stories, but I don&apos;t think that&apos;s the only reason. They were definitely not for kids and one or two were rather disturbing, but riveting all the same. I would only say that one had any real innuendo, but the themes were adult (or, at least, young adult).<br/><br/>I read a co</span>
  <span id="freeText16479086813600026411" style="display:none">This was a wonderful book. I am generally *not* a fan of short stories. I like stories that with lots of character development and there isn't time for that in short stories. Maybe this collection was improved by already "knowing" the stories, but I don't think that's the only reason. They were definitely not for kids and one or two were rather disturbing, but riveting all the same. I would only say that one had any real innuendo, but the themes were adult (or, at least, young adult).<br /><br />I read a collection of retellings by Robin McKinley, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/8091.The_Door_in_the_Hedge" title="The Door in the Hedge by Robin McKinley" rel="nofollow noopener"> The Door in the Hedge</a> that was okay, but I didn't particularly love. This was a completely different bird. I really enjoyed it.</span>
